/*******************************************************************************
	Inspired by GO
*******************************************************************************/
Using GO as base language for incant has huge advantages over C++
    I like the way it does slices and ranges and the way support classes use them seamlessly
        Still have questions about ranges
    switch is done the way I like (except for fall thru)
    for switch and if support initiating declarations. Not sure incant needs it WSS
    the support classes are SO well integrated (even tho not classes per se)
    concurrency support is off the chart amazing
    It has GC
    break and continue can take an argument (as in where to break to)
    no pointer arithmetic. I suppose we can live without it
    interfaces are shades of java implementations
    go doc tool is cool
    go methods can return multiple values. incant methods take one argument and return one value (both of which can contain multiple components). I like the incant approach but will revisit when and if we change base language to GO
    short variable declarations are interesting but incant does not bother with declarations
    GO does not use ; to end statements (uses line end???)
    I like the way flags are used, may solve my issues w/linking C++ flags to incant (or not)
    GO uses Type(x) instead of casting as (Type)x.
    raw string literals use `backquotes` and can extend over multiple lines
    strings are immutable. This will likely cause a problem w/incant
One implication of concurrency: we should be able to run interpret in a separate thread so it is only called once and when it runs out of input, wait on more input. Maybe same same w/parser
